03918nam a22004935i 9780520957664DE-B159720191221113333.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||191221s2018    cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209576647 a10.1525/97805209576642doi  a(DE-B1597)519225  a(OCoLC)1043673900  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aHIS0370002bisacsh1 aWhitfield, Susan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut.10aSilk, Slaves, and Stupas :bMaterial Culture of the Silk Road /cSusan Whitfield. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (376 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tNote on Transliteration and Names -- tIntroduction -- tOne. A Pair of Steppe Earrings -- tTwo. A Hellenistic Glass Bowl -- tThree. A Hoard of Kushan Coins -- tFour. Amluk Dara Stupa -- tFive. A Bactrian Ewer -- tSix. A Khotanese Plaque -- tSeven. The Blue Qurʾan -- tEight. A Byzantine Hunter Silk -- tNine. A Chinese Almanac -- tTen. The Unknown Slave -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFollowing her bestselling Life Along the Silk Road, Susan Whitfield widens her exploration of the great cultural highway with a new captivating portrait focusing on material things. Silk, Slaves, and Stupas tells the stories of ten very different objects, considering their interaction with the peoples and cultures of the Silk Road-those who made them, carried them, received them, used them, sold them, worshipped them, and, in more recent times, bought them, conserved them, and curated them. From a delicate pair of earrings from a steppe tomb to a massive stupa deep in Central Asia, a hoard of Kushan coins stored in an Ethiopian monastery to a Hellenistic glass bowl from a southern Chinese tomb, and a fragment of Byzantine silk wrapping the bones of a French saint to a Bactrian ewer depicting episodes from the Trojan War, these objects show us something of the cultural diversity and interaction along these trading routes of Afro-Eurasia.   Exploring the labor, tools, materials, and rituals behind these various objects, Whitfield infuses her narrative with delightful details as the objects journey through time, space, and meaning. Silk, Slaves, and Stupas is a lively, visual, and tangible way to understand the Silk Road and the cultural, economic, and technical changes of the late antique and medieval worlds.       aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Dez 2019) 7aHISTORY / World.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook-Package 2016-2018z978311063539308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook-Package 2018z978311066767708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUCal Press eBook Package Frontlist 2017-2018z978311065859040uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520957664423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520957664.jpg  a978-3-11-063539-3  UC Press eBook-Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  a978-3-11-065859-0  UCal Press eBook Package Frontlist 2017-2018c2017d2018  a978-3-11-066767-7  UC Press eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles